{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"df578093-674a-4264-89fd-89844955a331","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the simplest option for .NET apps and requires no extra installs beyond the .NET SDK.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need OS-level detail (drivers, kernel, native code):\n\nUse **PerfView** or **dotnet-trace** with the `--format speedscope` flag for a browser-based flamegraph:\n\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --format speedscope\n```\n\nThen open the `.speedscope.json` at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n### Key tips:\n- **`dotnet-trace`** — best for managed (.NET) code, low overhead.\n- **PerfView** — best when you also need native/kernel stacks or GC analysis.\n- **`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`** — useful for a quick live look at CPU %, GC, threadpool before tracing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b6a75a1-05c5-461d-8df3-c78026bed4ea","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"501C:28F9DD:21D2CA:29CFB0:69F5518D"},"id":"019f10a9-f17c-41fe-8453-3ae769168a76","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:21:28.206Z","parentId":"b599c8c5-a4de-47d1-9216-60d7324b1b44"}
